If money was not an object, I would come here more often. For now, this a place reserved only for special occasions. I treated my boyfriend here last Christmas. After cocktails, we had the tasting menu with wine parings. The wine parings seemed small at first, but it was the perfect amount to accompany each dish. The dishes were beautifully arranged and surprisingly generous. All courses are timed to perfection, with top notch service. They have a wonderful cheese cart, and very knowledgeable cheese person. We ordered a dessert that they prepare right by your table. This place is extremely well run. Nothing falls through the cracks, they even monitor who gets up to use the restroom in order to prevent a dish from going out to the table when you were away. The entire experience was perfect. I could have asked for better. They even give you a little pastry for the next morning.

I checked this place out a while back and only have good things to say about it. I even tried (with great Success) in replicating the meal at home. This is hands down one of the best places in the city. The food is a fair deal and the drinks are well you know, pricey, as with any place on this level. Everything about the place is fantastic and impeccable. If you can go. If you can't find a way (even if it means going solo).

I called first week of January to make a reservation for 2/20 and they only reservation I could get was at 9pm. It's okay since my fiance and I didn't have work on President's day. The day of, they called me in the afternoon and asked me if I would like to move my reservation to 8pm, even better. My fiance and I went to Gary Danko for our belated Valentine's day dinner and the experience we had with food and service were both very excellent. I was a little skeptical when friends told me not to order the 5 courses cause of their portion size. Boy I was wrong; they were very generous with their portion size. Both of us were so stuffed when we left. Here is what we ordered.. me: (4 courses) -Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Shimeji Mushrooms and Butternut Squash -- one of the best risottos I've ever had -Lemon Pepper Duck Breast with Duck Hash, Celery Root-Garlic Purée and Cardamom Poached Pears -- a little salty -Herb Crusted Loin of Lamb with Moroccan Lamb Sausage, Hummus, Spiced Eggplant Stew and Mint Yogurt -Flambéed Bananas with Mascarpone Filled Crèpes, Graham Cracker-Pecan Streusel and Vanilla Ice Cream -- lots of sugar but omg it was so tasty fiance: (5 course tasting menu) -Crispy Farm Egg with White Polenta, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, Frisée, Pancetta and Black Truffles -Seared Sea Scallops with Parsnip Purée, Spinach, Caramelized Onions and Black Truffles -- a little salty -Seared Filet of Beef with Crimini Mushrooms, Braised Shallots, Potato Cake and Black Truffles -A Selection of Farmhouse and Truffled Artisanal Cheeses -Black Truffle Crémeux with Vanilla Foam A few dishes were more on the salty side but I love salty food so I had no problems with them. The staff there were so attentive. I think we had 6-7 different people waited on us the whole night. One of the waiter suggested a half bottle American pinot noir from Oregon which was very good. The only thing I didn't like was the noise level inside the restaurant. I know that everyone was having a blast there but it was a little too loud for intimate setting. I can't wait to go back there and try the rest of the dishes!!!

This is a really special intimate place as soon as you step on their red carpet. They just think of everything. The hostess takes your coat, a staff waits near the crowded bar to take your drink order, the makeup mirror inside the "spa" restroom, along with the sound of trickling water, bread is put on your plate without you noticing, the "present" for the guest when they pay, the little leftover in a nice gift bag, a purse hanger, and the best part for me is the little plate of miniature desserts at the end. I feel like 10 people must have served us in 3 hours of eating. They remembered that this was a birthday celebration. I didn't have to remind or say anything. At the end, a candle on the most delicious passion fruit mousse came out for the honored person. This would be a great place to propose (hint, hint). I saw a lot of couples dining. One couple even had a baby in a stroller. The baby slept through the whole dinner (it must be the dim light). That is another special thing, you can actually hear and talk with no loud noises. Highlights: I love the scallops and the duck breast, perfectly done. I had the foie gras, but couldn't really enjoy it because of the video in my head. It did melt in my mouth. If you are a cheese lover, when they push the cheese cart to you, you might think you are in heaven. The starter curry soup just wakes up your palate. The choice is yours for the taking: 3 course, 5 course, or special menu. Reminds me of being on a cruise ship when you can pick and choose. My friend had 1 appetizer and 2 entrees. This is such a neat concept to me. It's a long meal so bring someone who you would enjoy to visit for 3 hours. Our reservation was for 9:00 p.m. My little friend didn't like the waiter asking if we needed a taxi or valet to get our car. She felt it was snobbish. She didn't feel the waiter was that personable, but I can see he was way too busy serving and tending to his job. If I were him, by 12 midnight, I'm down to my one string of patience.

I don't get all the hype about this place. I have eaten at a handful of restaurants in the bay area what are way better and way less money. I heard you pay for the service here. Well unfortunately we had a server who made a joke when we told him we were allergic to gluten. Then, when he brought us our food, he watched us start eating, and then halfway through the meal, he told us he had forgotten and there was gluten in the meal. Can you imagine? Is this what good service is? I started to panic, knowing I get very sick from gluten. He finally told us he was kidding and after realizing we were not happy with the joke. For all that money, I would have expected to at least not be made fun of for having celiac disease.

Now this is some fine dining! My fiancee took me here as a surprise for my birthday, and it was a pretty awesome experience! As you may know, you have a choice of a 3, 4, or 5-course dinner. You can choose any combination of appetizer, fish/seafood, meat/game birds, cheese and desserts. I elected for the 5-course dinner and went with the following (all of which I can recommend!): * Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Peaches * Seared Sea Scallops with Zucchini-Basil Purée, Tomato Fondue, Red Peppers, Haricot Vert and Shimeji Mushrooms * Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Sorrel Purée, Peas, Bacon, Pickled Jalapeos and Maple Glaze * Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Zucchini, Mushrooms, Chard and Tomato-Eggplant Confit * Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Roasted Peaches, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream The foie gras, pork belly, and warm butter cake were particularly good. You should note, though, that when they say sea scallops with an "s" at the end, they really mean 1 semi-large sea scallop. While it's true that I didn't pay for dinner this time, I must say that $102 for 5 courses is quite reasonable for fine dining. They will gladly box any leftovers that you have, and those boxes will be waiting for you next to the maître d' on your way out. Complimentary items included an amuse bouche soup, a morning bun for my fiancee, a passion fruit mousse cake for my birthday, and a plateful of chocolates. We requested and sat at a quarter-table, so that we could sit closer to each other, which was great. I can't wait to go back for another celebration!

I believe Gary Danko to be one of THE best restaurants in the world. Lucky for me, I've been here many, many times, and I have literally only had one dish that wasn't outstanding. My family comes here (from Australia) every time, and this time I was able to introduce it to someone new! Overall, every dish was perfectly executed - perfectly cooked, well seasoned, with great complementing flavors. The service was as usual outstanding. I have actually gotten this bar tender/waiter before and he's clearly very good at what he does. The couple of Manhattans served were also perfectly prepared. I started off with the risotto with lobster, rock shrimp, Shimeji mushroom, asparagus and peas. This is my sister's favourite dish. I have very few risottos, mainly because so many are just plain bad. I have even fewer creamy risottos. Pelago in Chicago should get a mention here because its absolutely sensational for Risotto. This lobster is a perfect balance - just enough cream for richness, perfectly cooked rice and sweet, fresh delicious lobster and shrimp. This was a fresh, well balanced dish (just check out the presentation). Seaared ahi tuna with avacado, nori, enoki mushroom and lemon soy dressing. Question - why is literally all fruits and vegetables better in SF? The avocados were amazing - creamy, fresh and delicious. The tuna fresh, delicious and served at the perfect temperature, the nori crunchy, the mushrooms earthy but sweet and the dressing refreshing. For my main, I had Herb crusted lamb loin with Cannellini beans braised lamb shoulder, barley and cumin mint yogurt. As you can clearly see, it is an sensationally perfectly cooked lamb loin, well seasoned. The crust that was achieved on the lamb gave it a nice crunch as you cut through the lamb. The lamb shoulder was rich and flavorful. The Cannellini beans were a hearty complement to the lamb and the cumin mint yoghurt gave a nice freshness to the dish. I've not had this dish before, but it has quickly become one of my favourites. It was always hard to go past the lemon pepper duck breast. And finally the souffle, as always perfectly executed, light and fluffy. A pet peeve of mine remains the cutting of a hole in the souffle and pouring sauces in. Yes the sauces were delicious, but I just don't like it.

I was counting down the days till my visit to Gary Danko and when the day arrived I made sure I had a healthy appetite, for destruction, to my figure. We arrived at the restaurant at around 6:30 and made our way through the doors and into a sophisticated and intimate setting. The room was well decorated with flowers but I must say there were other knick knacks that offset the whole vision. There were stained glass sculptures that just didn't quite feel cohesive with the rest of the restaurant, but it doesn't matter because the food makes everything ok. So, we were greeted at the door and then seated right away. We were missing someone from our party and thought that we would have to wait until our entire party showed up, but luckily they were kind enough to have sat us anyways. I live in Southern California and I don't get the opportunity to wine and dine at Gary Danko as often as I would like so I opted for the 4 course. I seriously would have ordered the 5 course but I didn't want to look like a McFatty. The menu was overwhelming because I wanted to eat everything but unfortunately I had to narrow my choices down to 4. I started with an amuse bouche of pea and ramp soup with a rock shrimp tempura. The soup was sweet and subtle. The rock shrimp tempura was cooked perfectly which retained its sweetness and texture Lobster and Fennel Bisque with Dungeness Crab, Peppers and Saffron-Orange Rémoulade was my first dish. I was served with a bowl that had crab meat in the center and then later the bisque was poured into my bowl in front of me. I thought it was a nice touch on their tableside presentation. At first smell the bisque was very aromatic. The sweetness from the lobster, crab, peppers and saffron paired with the fennel came together to create a very delicate dish Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon was the next on my list. I always tell myself to try something different when dining at Gary Danko but I tend to always order the Maine Lobster because it's that good. The dish itself is very simple, light, and well executed. The lobster was sweet and it had a nice bite to it. The potato puree was creamy and melted in my mouth. An earthy touch was given off by the trumpet mushroom and a hint of freshness from the tarragon and edamame. Very simple ingredients and a very unforgettable dish Coriander Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spatzle was the beginning to my meat encounters. This was definitely a beefy/hearty dish. My bison was medium rare as suggested because if its low fat content, and was sweet and rich in flavor. I love cipollini onions because of its sweetness and what is there to not love about trumpet mushrooms? The spatzle was light and chewy and gave a great textual balance. Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Ramp Purée, Fava Beans, Artichokes and Maple Glaze was my last dish. The pork belly had some fat which left a tender and juicy piece of pork belly in MY belly. The tender loin was also tender (hence the name) and delicious. The maple glaze gave the entire dish a hint of sweetness while the potato-ramp puree, fava beans, and artichoke's subtle flavors were a nice addition to cut through the heaviness of the dish. I ended my fabulous meal with a warm Louisiana butter cake with caramelized apples, huckleberry compote and vanilla ice cream. The dessert wasn't too sweet and the butter cake was warm, moist, and perfect. Everyone at Gary Danko was friendly and the service was phenomenal as always. I picked at everyone's food and found all of their dishes were also delicious. This was my fourth time dining with them and I'm sure there will be more to come, and hopefully I can finally break my Maine Lobster addiction the next time around.

I first wanted to try this restaurant after hearing Anthony Bourdain rant about how good it was on No Reservations. I'm not Anthony "Dirty Martinis" Bourdain, so I made a reservation. Two months and many broken hearts later, I finally arrived with some change in my pocket and a twinkle in my eye. After trying their scallops, I had an epiphany. Gary Danko is a fairy. No wait, he's THE Fairy. I'm not sure if it's actually him or a legion of magical talking woodland creatures back in that kitchen, but D******MN my meal was magical! This is one of those fancy places with fancy napkins that actually walks the walk. Sure, any schmuck with an American Express can walk into any high priced establishment and drop $200 on a meal for two and feel like the Queen of England. There's an illusion of quality and exclusivity that occurs when something is expensive. At Danko's, I never felt like I was paying for an illusion. To start off with, the meals here are ordered by course size. You can select between having 3 courses, 4 courses, or 5 courses. While the main menu is broken down in to the categories of appetizers, seafood, meats, and desserts you are allowed to make any combination of selections in the order you want to eat them. The staff then varies the amount of food in each dish depending upon the order you tell your waiter/waitress. To make this food math simple, an example of their customizable platter size is if you order the scallops as your first item (appetizer), you'll get 2. If you order it third or fourth (entree), you'll get a tasty scallop party of 5. They have an excellent wine menu, at least the one I tried. I didn't drink very much this time, as I had no intention of being banned or publicly humiliated in front of fabulously wealthy people whom I am sure to be intimate friends with one day. Their service is amazing. We had at least 10 staff members come by our table. They seem to have a person for each function. Our waiter in charge of clean plates and silverware must have had a bomb strapped to his crotch, set to go off if any customer had a dirty plate or utensils for more than 3 seconds. I applaud your creative methods of motivation! Some quick highlights of Gary's children that I love the most: - Seared Scallops - Farmer's Egg - Lobster - Pork Tenderloin and Pork Belly - Cheese selection - Chocolate Souffle - Duck - Complimentary small desserts sampler! - Complimentary dessert parting gift! Their cheese selection is unique and worth mentioning because I'm a cheese lover and you're my captive audience. When you select this as one of your courses, a cart of various cheeses come out and you are allowed to sample and select a few. The selection was amazing, and I had a difficult time choosing. The waiter was very knowledgeable about all the cheeses, and I found it quite enjoyable to debate goat versus cow curds with him. If you are curious, he won the debate with goat (Bravo good sir!). An interesting thing occurred during my dinner, something which can only be explained with fairy magic. There was something about sitting and having an incredibly expensive but delicious meal that made people want to talk to other tables. Seeing me struggle with the menu (hint: everything looks amazing), all manners of rich and well cultured individuals would lean in and impart some foodie wisdom on the best items there. Not only did I experience this with every neighboring table, but once those people left I would experience it all over again with the new people that arrive! Last random rant - I ate the only brownie on my girlfriend and I's complimentary dessert sampler in a vain attempt at humor (okay, I just wanted the brownie). She heard from our neighboring table that it was their favorite dessert, so I was in deep doo doo. Our waiter, upon hearing this, winks conspiratorially at me and tells me to meet him at the front door. In a minute, he sneaks out with a small box that contained a sampling of every single dessert on the tray! I thank you kind Saint, for you surely have saved me from convincing my coworkers that I walked into a door knob the next day! All in all, an amazing meal that came with amazing memories that could only be described as Magical (wait for it)... so you could say... (wait for it) I had a Fairy Magical evening! ...sorry, I had to. :(

What a cool name! Who is Gary Danko, I want to meet him and see what he is all about! And you better believe it, I really would love to go here someday. I hope that's clear. My mom, if I could bring here, she would be proud. It would be a good idea to get a job paying me more dollars than I have sense, but who's stopping me, this is America! Five stars for food.

Went on a date here and it was absolutely one of my top five favorite meals ever. I even liked it better than The French Laundry (though that might have partially been due to my company). Typically choosing a favorite restaurant is just about as hard as choosing a favorite book or album. In this case, however, Gary Danko is easily the best restaurant in the city. The food? Perfect balance of flavors, perfect preparation. And those blinis, oh, those blinis! I could probably eat a hundred of those buttery, savory blinis in one sitting. My mouth waters just thinking of them. When I went, my dining partner and I both had the prix fixe menu--I had the 3-course and he, the 4-course. Stand-outs included the corn soup and the pan-seared bass. $73 for 3 courses might seem steep at first glance, but in reality, it's a bargain for the unbeatable quality of the food and service here. Where Gary Danko really transcends any typical restaurant experience, though, is in the impeccable service. Admittedly, I'm very picky about service--even if a restaurant has amazing food, I'll refuse to return if the service is poor. At HD, from start to finish, the service was smooth, streamlined, beautiful. Every person you interact with, from the hostess to the manager to the server, treats you as an important and valued guest. Absolutely no snobbery to be found here despite the restaurant's high profile status. I was impressed by our server's knowledge of the menu--he knew all the ingredients and cooking preparation of any dish we asked about and also made some great suggestions for us based on our tastes. Many of the servers are sommeliers here too, so they'll be able to make informed wine suggestions. Our server also performed a table-side preparation of my bananas foster. Food, service, pyrotechnics--what more could you ask for?

    Now this is some fine dining! My fiancee took me here as a surprise for my birthday, and it was a pretty awesome experience!

    As you may know, you have a choice of a 3, 4, or 5-course dinner. You can choose any combination of appetizer, fish/seafood, meat/game birds, cheese and desserts. I elected for the 5-course dinner and went with the following (all of which I can recommend!):

    * Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Peaches
    * Seared Sea Scallops with Zucchini-Basil Purée, Tomato Fondue, Red Peppers, Haricot Vert and Shimeji Mushrooms
    * Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Sorrel Purée, Peas, Bacon, Pickled Jalapeos and Maple Glaze
    * Seared Filet of Beef with Yukon Potatoes, Zucchini, Mushrooms, Chard and Tomato-Eggplant Confit
    * Warm Louisiana Butter Cake with Roasted Peaches, Huckleberry Compote and Vanilla Ice Cream

    The foie gras, pork belly, and warm butter cake were particularly good. You should note, though, that when they say sea scallops with an "s" at the end, they really mean 1 semi-large sea scallop.

    While it's true that I didn't pay for dinner this time, I must say that $102 for 5 courses is quite reasonable for fine dining.

    They will gladly box any leftovers that you have, and those boxes will be waiting for you next to the maître d' on your way out. Complimentary items included an amuse bouche soup, a morning bun for my fiancee, a passion fruit mousse cake for my birthday, and a plateful of chocolates.

    We requested and sat at a quarter-table, so that we could sit closer to each other, which was great. I can't wait to go back for another celebration!

    5/4/2012

    I believe Gary Danko to be one of THE best restaurants in the world.  Lucky for me, I've been here many, many times, and I have literally only had one dish that wasn't outstanding.  My family comes here (from Australia) every time, and this time I was able to introduce it to someone new!  Overall, every dish was perfectly executed - perfectly cooked, well seasoned, with great complementing flavors.  The service was as usual outstanding.  I have actually gotten this bar tender/waiter before and he's clearly very good at what he does.  The couple of Manhattans served were also perfectly prepared.

    I started off with the risotto with lobster, rock shrimp, Shimeji mushroom, asparagus and peas.  This is my sister's favourite dish.  I have very few risottos, mainly because so many are just plain bad. I have even fewer creamy risottos.  Pelago in Chicago should get a mention here because its absolutely sensational for Risotto.  This lobster is a perfect balance - just enough cream for richness, perfectly cooked rice and sweet, fresh delicious lobster and shrimp.

    This was a fresh, well balanced dish (just check out the presentation).  Seaared ahi tuna with avacado, nori, enoki mushroom and lemon soy dressing.  Question - why is literally all fruits and vegetables better in SF? The avocados were amazing - creamy, fresh and delicious.  The tuna fresh, delicious and served at the perfect temperature, the nori crunchy, the mushrooms earthy but sweet and the dressing refreshing.  

    For my main, I had Herb crusted lamb loin with Cannellini beans braised lamb shoulder, barley and cumin mint yogurt.  As you can clearly see, it is an sensationally perfectly cooked lamb loin, well seasoned.  The crust that was achieved on the lamb gave it a nice crunch as you cut through the lamb.  The lamb shoulder was rich and flavorful.  The Cannellini beans were a hearty complement to the lamb and the cumin mint yoghurt gave a nice freshness to the dish.  I've not had this dish before, but it has quickly become one of my favourites.  It was always hard to go past the lemon pepper duck breast.

    And finally the souffle, as always perfectly executed, light and fluffy.  A pet peeve of mine remains the cutting of a hole in the souffle and pouring sauces in. Yes the sauces were delicious, but I just don't like it.

    5/21/2010

    I was counting down the days till my visit to Gary Danko and when the day arrived I made sure I had a healthy appetite, for destruction, to my figure.

    We arrived at the restaurant at around 6:30 and made our way through the doors and into a sophisticated and intimate setting. The room was well decorated with flowers but I must say there were other knick knacks that offset the whole vision. There were stained glass sculptures that just didn't quite feel cohesive with the rest of the restaurant, but it doesn't matter because the food makes everything ok. So, we were greeted at the door and then seated right away. We were missing someone from our party and thought that we would have to wait until our entire party showed up, but luckily they were kind enough to have sat us anyways.

    I live in Southern California and I don't get the opportunity to wine and dine at Gary Danko as often as I would like so I opted for the 4 course. I seriously would have ordered the 5 course but I didn't want to look like a McFatty. The menu was overwhelming because I wanted to eat everything but unfortunately I had to narrow my choices down to 4.

    I started with an amuse bouche of pea and ramp soup with a rock shrimp tempura. The soup was sweet and subtle. The rock shrimp tempura was cooked perfectly which retained its sweetness and texture

    Lobster and Fennel Bisque with Dungeness Crab, Peppers and Saffron-Orange Rémoulade was my first dish. I was served with a bowl that had crab meat in the center and then later the bisque was poured into my bowl in front of me. I thought it was a nice touch on their tableside presentation. At first smell the bisque was very aromatic. The sweetness from the lobster, crab, peppers and saffron paired with the fennel came together to create a very delicate dish

    Roast Maine Lobster with Potato Purée, Black Trumpet Mushrooms, Edamame and Tarragon was the next on my list. I always tell myself to try something different when dining at Gary Danko but I tend to always order the Maine Lobster because it's that good. The dish itself is very simple, light, and well executed. The lobster was sweet and it had a nice bite to it. The potato puree was creamy and melted in my mouth. An earthy touch was given off by the trumpet mushroom and a hint of freshness from the tarragon and edamame.  Very simple ingredients and a very unforgettable dish

    Coriander Crusted Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spatzle was the beginning to my meat encounters. This was definitely a beefy/hearty dish. My bison was medium rare as suggested because if its low fat content, and was sweet and rich in flavor. I love cipollini onions because of its sweetness and what is there to not love about trumpet mushrooms? The spatzle was light and chewy and gave a great textual balance.

    Roasted Pork Belly and Tenderloin with Potato-Ramp Purée, Fava Beans, Artichokes and Maple Glaze was my last dish. The pork belly had some fat which left a tender and juicy piece of pork belly in MY belly. The tender loin was also tender (hence the name) and delicious. The maple glaze gave the entire dish a hint of sweetness while the potato-ramp puree, fava beans, and artichoke's subtle flavors were a nice addition to cut through the heaviness of the dish.

    I ended my fabulous meal with a warm Louisiana butter cake with caramelized apples, huckleberry compote and vanilla ice cream. The dessert wasn't too sweet and the butter cake was warm, moist, and perfect.

    Everyone at Gary Danko was friendly and the service was phenomenal as always. I picked at everyone's food and found all of their dishes were also delicious. This was my fourth time dining with them and I'm sure there will be more to come, and hopefully I can finally break my Maine Lobster addiction the next time around.

    5/31/2010

    I first wanted to try this restaurant after hearing Anthony Bourdain rant about how good it was on No Reservations. I'm not Anthony "Dirty Martinis" Bourdain, so I made a reservation. Two months and many broken hearts later, I finally arrived with some change in my pocket and a twinkle in my eye.

    After trying their scallops, I had an epiphany.

    Gary Danko is a fairy. No wait, he's THE Fairy.

    I'm not sure if it's actually him or a legion of magical talking woodland creatures back in that kitchen, but D******MN my meal was magical!

    This is one of those fancy places with fancy napkins that actually walks the walk. Sure, any schmuck with an American Express can walk into any high priced establishment and drop $200 on a meal for two and feel like the Queen of England. There's an illusion of quality and exclusivity that occurs when something is expensive. At Danko's, I never felt like I was paying for an illusion.

    To start off with, the meals here are ordered by course size. You can select between having 3 courses, 4 courses, or 5 courses. While the main menu is broken down in to the categories of appetizers, seafood, meats, and desserts you are allowed to make any combination of selections in the order you want to eat them. The staff then varies the amount of food in each dish depending upon the order you tell your waiter/waitress.

    To make this food math simple, an example of their customizable platter size is if you order the scallops as your first item (appetizer), you'll get 2. If you order it third or fourth (entree), you'll get a tasty scallop party of 5.

    They have an excellent wine menu, at least the one I tried. I didn't drink very much this time, as I had no intention of being banned or publicly humiliated in front of fabulously wealthy people whom I am sure to be intimate friends with one day.

    Their service is amazing. We had at least 10 staff members come by our table. They seem to have a person for each function. Our waiter in charge of clean plates and silverware must have had a bomb strapped to his crotch, set to go off if any customer had a dirty plate or utensils for more than 3 seconds. I applaud your creative methods of motivation!

    Some quick highlights of Gary's children that I love the most:
    - Seared Scallops
    - Farmer's Egg
    - Lobster
    - Pork Tenderloin and Pork Belly
    - Cheese selection
    - Chocolate Souffle
    - Duck
    - Complimentary small desserts sampler!
    - Complimentary dessert parting gift!

    Their cheese selection is unique and worth mentioning because I'm a cheese lover and you're my captive audience. When you select this as one of your courses, a cart of various cheeses come out and you are allowed to sample and select a few. The selection was amazing, and I had a difficult time choosing. The waiter was very knowledgeable about all the cheeses, and I found it quite enjoyable to debate goat versus cow curds with him. If you are curious, he won the debate with goat (Bravo good sir!).

    An interesting thing occurred during my dinner, something which can only be explained with fairy magic. There was something about sitting and having an incredibly expensive but delicious meal that made people want to talk to other tables. Seeing me struggle with the menu (hint: everything looks amazing), all manners of rich and well cultured individuals would lean in and impart some foodie wisdom on the best items there. Not only did I experience this with every neighboring table, but once those people left I would experience it all over again with the new people that arrive!

    Last random rant - I ate the only brownie on my girlfriend and I's complimentary dessert sampler in a vain attempt at humor (okay, I just wanted the brownie). She heard from our neighboring table that it was their favorite dessert, so I was in deep doo doo. Our waiter, upon hearing this, winks conspiratorially at me and tells me to meet him at the front door. In a minute, he sneaks out with a small box that contained a sampling of every single dessert on the tray! I thank you kind Saint, for you surely have saved me from convincing my coworkers that I walked into a door knob the next day!

    All in all, an amazing meal that came with amazing memories that could only be described as Magical (wait for it)... so you could say... (wait for it) I had a Fairy Magical evening!

    ...sorry, I had to. :(

    7/6/2013

    Typically choosing a favorite restaurant is just about as hard as choosing a favorite book or album. In this case, however, Gary Danko is easily the best restaurant in the city.

    The food? Perfect balance of flavors, perfect preparation. And those blinis, oh, those blinis! I could probably eat a hundred of those buttery, savory blinis in one sitting. My mouth waters just thinking of them.

    When I went, my dining partner and I both had the prix fixe menu--I had the 3-course and he, the 4-course.  Stand-outs included the corn soup and the pan-seared bass. $73 for 3 courses might seem steep at first glance, but in reality, it's a bargain for the unbeatable quality of the food and service here.

    Where Gary Danko really transcends any typical restaurant experience, though, is in the impeccable service. Admittedly, I'm very picky about service--even if a restaurant has amazing food, I'll refuse to return if the service is poor. At HD, from start to finish, the service was smooth, streamlined, beautiful. Every person you interact with, from the hostess to the manager to the server, treats you as an important and valued guest. Absolutely no snobbery to be found here despite the restaurant's high profile status. I was impressed by our server's knowledge of the menu--he knew all the ingredients and cooking preparation of any dish we asked about and also made some great suggestions for us based on our tastes. Many of the servers are sommeliers here too, so they'll be able to make informed wine suggestions.

    Our server also performed a table-side preparation of my bananas foster. Food, service, pyrotechnics--what more could you ask for?
